Salafist-inspired protesters comprised mostly of unenrolled students staged a sit-in to demonstrate against a law preventing women from attending Manouba University--a secular, public school--wearing the niqab. The salafist protesters also demanded a place for prayer.

On 19 December 2011, battles with police and military continued, 3 more reported dead from clashes. Live rounds were reported fired by security forces reported while rioters threw Molotov cocktails. 17 people were killed in total between Dec.16-19, including some who later died of their injuries (extra fatalities coded on Dec.18) while 12 were wounded over the two day clash.

In another event, Millat Tractor Factory Workers Union has warned the federal government to withdraw 17 percent General Sales tax from this industry otherwise they would launch a long march towards Islamabad. The warning was issued by the factory workers during a protest at Sheikhupura Road. The protesters chanted slogans against the anti-industry and agriculture policies of the government.

Tahrir Square protests continue. Protesters vow to remain until civilian rule is brought to the country. Medical officials say that one demonstrator has been killed by unknown individuals outside the countries Cabinet building.
On Nov 26, a motorcade of BNP leaders and activists on way to join the BNP chairperson's Kushtia rally came under attack by rioters in Gangni upazila of Meherpur.

actor2: Police Forces of the Democratic Republic of Congo (2001-2019)
notes: UDPS supporters gather to show support for their candidate as he arrives at the airport. Police disperse with teargas, two killed in clashed between them.

A group of 100 protesters gather at Tripoli International Airport to block a Tunisian passenger aircraft from taking off to protest the Libyan transitional government. They said they wanted the Libyan government to open an investigation into a clash last week in which several members of the Souq al-Juma militia were killed.
A group of 60 woman gather outside the office of Prime Minister Abdurrahim el-Keib believing the government is failing to help woman who were sexually assaulted at the hands of Gaddafis forces.

Government school teachers held protest rally against decision of Punjab Government to abolish 50 percent quota of reserve seats for 'in service teachers'.
Two prisoners were killed and five wounded when the prison security forces used firearms during a riot in Bongor prison.

Several men belonging to the Issaq/Essa Musa/Adan Essa sub clan attacked the residence of the Governor of Sahil Region with sticks. The attack was reported to be motivated by anger about the death of a man who was killed by the police after he tried to escape the police station where he was held. The man was arrested on an order from the Governor on 23/11/2011. The reason for the arrest remains unclear. The attackers were repulsed by the guards of the Governor.

On 26 November 2011, residents of the village of Akwa in the district of Dyarb Ngim set fire to tires and blocked the main road through the town to condemn recent insecurity in the town. [size=not reported]
The nurses of All Balochistan Nursing Federation Balochistan chapter observed black day and took out rally to protest what they said torture on nurses by police and traders in Lahore.
On Nov 26, Bangladesh Poribesh Andolon (Bapa) staged a protest in Sylhet to raise their voice against the India's unilateral move for Tipaimukh dam project in the state of Manipur of India.
From November 24 - 30, BNP staged protests in Sylht city against the construction of a dam.
On Nov 26, BCL activists staged a sit-in on campus in Noakhali University, Noakhali district, against the Regent Board of the university did not withdraw the expulsion order immediately.

On Nov 26, officials and employees of Dhaka City Corporation (DCC) observed three-hour pen down strike to protest splitting of the Corporation and clashed with police that left at least 25 people injured.

On Nov 26, students of Habibullah Bahar University College and workers of an under-construction building at Kakrail in Dhaka locked into a clash blocking Malibagh-Kakrail road for an hour. Clash erupted as three students of the college protested falling of a piece of tiles on a pedestrian from the 18-storey building of Future Group.

On Nov 26, hundreds of protesters joined a grand rally at Central Shaheed Minar in Dhaka called by National Committee to Protect Oil, Gas, Mineral Resources, Power, and Ports to realise their seven-point demand.

notes: On Nov 26, in Meherpur, a bus and microbus carrying BNP leaders and workers from Gangni to Kushtia for joining the road march led by Khaleda Zia to Khulna came under attack allegedly by BCL and Jubo League activists.

Cadres of Tharuhat Nepal vandalized and set fire on two trucks in Dang district. Meanwhile, traffic in the district resumed after only 11 in the morning when the government and the Tharuhat leaders reached an agreement to stop the protests. The Tharuhat Nepal and other fringe parties had called the bandh putting forth the demands of dissolving the Constituent Assembly, among others.
Residents protest crime in Delft.

Students' organisations condemned the attack by the NATO forces on the check post of the Pakistani troops. The Islami Jamiat-e-Talba (IJT) protested against the attack by the NATO forces and demanded the government part ways with NATO in the war on terror.

On 26 November 2011, nearly 2.000 workers protested at Dangkor district hall, in Phnom Penh, after the arrest of a union leader from the Labour Friendship Union at Cambo Handsome Ltd garment factory. The unionist was released following the protest.

On 25 November 2011, thousands of protesters marched in Tahrir Square demanded the resignation of the military leaders responsible for violence in recent days. Protesters disarmed a group of thugs who arrived seeking to cause trouble. The protesters also began a multi-day sit in. [size=thousands]
On 25 November 2011, thousands of protesters gathered in Abbasiya Square in Cairo to show solidarity with the SCAF, calling themselves the "Million Man March of the Silent Majority". [size=thousands]

Nurses from different state-run hospitals staged a protest demonstration at Provincial Sandeman Hospital to support the demands of their protesting colleagues in Lahore and elsewhere in the Punjab. Nursing Federation of Balochistan had strongly condemned manhandling of protesting nurses by Police in Lahore.

On November 25, at least 10 drivers of Nasiman and easy bikes were hurt and a number of vehicle damaged during a day-long strike enforced by the Bangladesh Road Transport Owners Association, Jessore on 18 routes. They demanded cancellation of fuel price hike, repair of the damaged roads and ban on the movements of human haulers and easy bikes (battery-run three-wheelers).
From November 24 - 30, BNP staged protests in Sylht city against the construction of a dam.
Unhappy locals from Mdhila took off to Gafsa Phosphates Companys (GIC) headquarters in the capital Tunis to protest the outcome of GIC recruitment exams which they say are "falsified" and "unfair".

Protesters blocked the entrance to the Egyptian cabinet HQ in a bid to prevent the newly-named PM Kamal al-Ganzuri from entering the building.

Residents in Pathum Thani's Rangsit area demolished a section of a sandbag fence intended to facilitate the drying of Rangsit Market. Around 100 people had come to demonstrate and started dismantling the sandbags after local and Irrigation Department officials failed to meet them.

Bang Khae residents blocked a section of the Western Outer Ring Road to demand an explanation from the government of its "unfair" flood-prevention measures. The group refused to disperse at the request of police. Angry motorists were kept away from the demonstrators.

About 100 residents from Bangkok's Thawi Watthana, Taling Chan and Bang Kae districts closed a section of Kanchanapisek road at Khlong Bang Chuek Nang to demand City Hall clarify its management plan for the recent flooding.

Protester and police clash for the 6th straight day. Police fire teargas and rubber bullets at the demonstrators. Many report the use of live ammunition by police. The fatality count from the 6 days of protests has reached 41 (38 coded in previous events). As many as 180 police and a number of soldiers have been reported injured in the clashes.

The journalists from Karak District protested against the attack on a local journalist by Shah Jehan, the brother of Member Provincial Assembly (MPA) Malik Qasim Khan over publishing a news item in his weekly against Malik Qasim Khan. They alleged that Qasim, accompanied by other men, had also broken the camera and mobile phone of the journalist.
Thousands of nurses from all public sector hospitals in the province staged a protest demonstration in front of Lahore press club to press their demand of pay raise and promotion.

A few unidentified armed men after holding the leader of Pakistan Muslim League-Functional (PML-F) and former Sindh Minister, Mir Nasir Khan Khoso hostage at gunpoint looted cash, mobile phone and other valuables and managed to flee from the scene. A large number of the people of Khoso community recorded a protest demonstration and demanded of the concerned authorities for immediate arrest of accused robbers.

The activists of Trade Union Kandhkot led by Mir Haibat Khan Bajkani staged a protest demonstration against actions of the PPL Gas Field Kandhkot. They protested against local people not being provided with job oppurtunities in the PPL Gas Field Kandhkot.

Violence resumed in the cities of Om Larayes and Mdhilla. The head of the company of phosphates of Gafsa (CPG) has been largely burned and its warehouses have been looted. Scuffles between security forces and protestors broke out.

Rioters protested the distribution of polling stations. Several houses were burned, some people injured & the CENI warehouse was ransaked.

On Nov 24, local units of BNP brought out a large procession in Sylhet city in protest against India's unilateral decision to build Tipaimukh dam on the Barak River that would affect downstream rivers Surma and Kushiara in Sylhet region of Bangladesh.

On Nov 24, in Pabna, at least 50 BNP activists including two central leaders were injured as the two rival factions of the party clashed over chanting slogans at the preparatory meeting for Begum Khaleda Zia's Southern region road march and rally at Dashuria.
On Nov 24, at least 50 people were injured in a BNP factional clash at Dasuria in Iswardi upazila. The clash was a sequel to previous enmity between the groups.
On Nov 24, Steps Towards Development held a rally to raise social conscience against violence against women and protest sexual harassment in Dhaka.
Clashes were reported in Mahalla between security forces and protesters, coinciding with ongoing protests against military rule throughout Egypt.

The transport of phosphate from the factories of the Gafsa Phosphate Company (GIC) to the factories of GCT in Mdhila, Gabes and Skhira was paralyzed by sit-ins organized. The transfer of production from Gafsa to the commercial port of Sfax was also interrupted due to the sit-ins held by many unemployed people in the train station of El Ksar. Similarly, freight and passengers transport by train in the governorate of Gafsa was interrupted following a protest by young unemployed people, particularly in El Ksar and Metlaoui.

All Pakistan Trade Union Federation (APTUF) on held a protest rally at the Lahore Press Club against high inflation, economic crises in railway, lack of law and order, anti-worker clauses in the 2011 Industrial Relations Ordinance and implementation of minimum wages.

The offices of the Gafsa Phosphate Company (GIC), in the districts of Mdhilla and Om Larayes, in Gafsa, were burnt down and the companies warehouses looted, following the announcement of its staffing competition results, deemed unfair by local applicants. 76 people were injured by tear gas in the two towns.

Frustrated by the month-long inundation of their homes, residents from Thanya Buri district blocked the Kaew Nimit Bridge in Thanya Buri district and threatened to breach a section of a flood barrier. Location coded at Rangsit, seat of Thanyaburi.

A demonstration was held at a section of a flood barrier near an Air Force unit in Pathum Thani. The demonstrators, numbering about 300, breached a section despite some 500 policemen guarding it, letting out a deluge of flood water.
About 100 Pathum Thani residents blocked an inbound toll way, leading to clash with motorists, which resulted in one injury.

Martyrs Families and victims of the Janandolan staged a sit-in demonstration at the Gate No. 3 of the Prime Minister's official residence at Baluwatar, and tried to disrupt the Prime Minister's movement. They staged the sit-in demonstration, demanding to implement past agreements and form a commission for necessary arrangement for them. Police have arrested 10 activists, who disrupted the traffic, under control.

On 23 November 2011, rioters clashed with police on Al Bustan Street in Talaat Harb Square with demonstrators erecting iron barriers to try and prevent security forces from entering nearby Tahrir Square. Dozens of rioters were wounded by tear gas and rubber bullets. [size=not reported]
University students from Cairo, Ain Shams and Helwan universities marched to Tahrir Square on Wednesday.
University students from Cairo, Ain Shams and Helwan universities marched to Tahrir Square on Wednesday.

Hundreds of residents of Baarsiigo area in Burao town held a demonstration against the local administrations decision to sell a plot of land for business use in their area. The demonstrators temporarily blocked the road leading to the offices of the local administration with stones and burning tires. The situation calmed down after the Mayor of Burao held a meeting with representatives of the demonstrators.
The citizens of Warah recorded a protest demonstration against the acute shortage of drinking water.

Angry villagers of Mdilla attacked the local offices of the Gafsa Phosphate Company after the announcement of results for a new hiring competition. 76 people were injured by tear gas in the two towns.
Demonstrators cut off the main road and burned out in the streets. The military dispersed the crowd with tear gas and shots fired in the air.
On Nov 23, a mob beat a youth to death suspecting him to be a thief in Khulna city.
On Nov 23, different organisations protested in Sylhet city against the attempt of constructing Tipaimukh dam on the Barak river at Tipaimukh in Manipur state of India.

On Nov 23, students of Premier University vandalised auto-rickshaws and other vehicles at a CNG refilling station on the ground floor of their university building at Wasa intersection in Chittagong over a firing incident.

On Nov 23, local citizens' committee formed a human chain in front of Shaheed Satu Hall in Chapainawabganj town demanding introduction of intercity train from the town, setting up of a bypass rail line at Amanura and protesting low quality repair work on Amanura-Chapainawabganj rail line.

On Nov 23, at least 50 people, including women and children, were injured in a clash between two groups of villagers in Brahambaria Sadar upazila following an altercation over selling of Bananas in local market.
On 23 Nov, residents staged a protest in Peliyagoda (Kelaniya, Gampaha) against the alleged abduction of a businessman, owner of three fisheries outlets.
Civil society members took out a protest rally against discharge of a case and release of the principal who allegedly molested a schoolgirl at his office in the Shahbaz Road area.
A protest was staged outside the US embassy in Kathmandu city, Central, on 23 November, against Monsanto seeds in Nepal.
Riots in Thala and Feriana.
Riots in Thala and Feriana.
Clashes near the security directorate office in the Smouha area of Alexandria on Nov.22 carried over into the morning of Nov.23.
Hundreds of people marched from Al-Qaed Ibhrahim Mosque to the Northern District military leadership HQ following days of clashes with security forces in Alexandria.
University students from Cairo, Ain Shams and Helwan universities marched to Tahrir Square on Wednesday.
Clashes were reported in Mahalla between security forces and protesters, coinciding with ongoing protests against military rule throughout Egypt.
Hundreds have been injured in protests and clashes with police across Egypt, including in Ismailia.

A smaller peaceful demonstration was held in Kasserine, gathering around 200 people as a result of the Constituent Assemblys failure to include the names of Kasserines dead in a list of martyrs of the Tunisian Revolution.

On 23 November 2011, hotel workers protested outside the Angkor Village Hotel and Resort, in Siem Reap city, to call for the reinstatement of workers who had been unlawfully sacked for unionizing. The police ended the protest and detained two unionists.
The Jamaat-i-Islami (JI) held protests in multiple cities against the Federal Cabinet's decision to grant Most Favoured Nation (MFN) status to India.The JI demanded a ban on trade with India.

Nearly 1,000 Nonthaburi residents gathered in protest at city hall in order to hear the provincial governor's response to their demands as well as continue to threaten to destroy floodwalls and prolong their protest.

On 22 November 2011, around 30 students gathered at Surat Thani Primary Educational Service Area Office 1 in tambon Makham Tia, Mueang Surat Thani District, Surat Thani, Thailand, demanding justice for a teacher who was transferred after having taken part in a protest to oust the school's former principal. [size=around 30]

Police arrested 18 persons, including former Environment Minister and regional leader, for holding a torch rally to protest against the extension of CA term in Kathmandu. The rally was meant to send a message that CA had already failed so it should not be extended further. No other details were reported.

On 22 November 2011, the death toll from confrontations between rioters, including students and Syrians who marched in solidarity, and police around Egypt has reached 30 (26 coded in previous events), the health ministry said on Tuesday, as the violence raged into a fourth straight day, including in among tens of thousands of protesters and large numbers of police in Tahrir Square and the nearby American University. Fatalities for events on the 22nd coded to 4.

Demonstrators gather in Pretoria to protest a controversial bill passing through parliament.
Demonstrators gather in Johannesburg to protest a controversial bill passing through parliament.

The nurses had been holding protests for the last five days for health professional allowances and other demands in Multan and other cities of southern Punjab. They refused to attend to patients at emergency wards and outpatient clinics against the government's failure to meet their demands.
Citizens have staged a protest rally against unannounced and prolonged load shedding on the night between Tuesday and Wednesday and blocked Shahrah-e-Pakistan.
Protests were held in Suez; no clashes were reported.

More than 500 protesters, among them editors and journalists, gathered near Parliament, calling for the "unjust" Protection of State Information Bill not to be passed into law. Protesters dubbed the gathering "Black Tuesday."

The leaders of JSMM Sakrand chapter staged a protest demonstration outside the Sakrand Press Club against the arrest of their party leaders. They demanded for the immediate release of the arrested party leaders.
Protests were reported in several Egyptian governorates in solidarity with those going on in Tahrir Square (specific locations not provided).

On Nov 22, students of Narail Government Victoria College formed a human chain in front of the deputy commissioner's office in Narail demanding immediate arrest of the killer of Naznin Nahar Mili, a student of the college.
On Nov 22, in Joypurhat, shop owners on staged demonstrations and laid a siege to the DC's Office in the town in protest against fines imposed on them by a mobile court.

On Nov 22, some Dhaka University students physically assaulted a photographer of The Daily Star in presence of a contingent of police, as he took snaps while the students were beating up another person in front of the Faculty of Fine Arts on Campus.

Residents protest that the mayors office over electricity problems.
Gambias election campaign wrapped up Tuesday with rival presidential candidates staging rallies in the tiny capital Banjul ahead of the poll tipped to hand incumbent Yahya Jammeh a fourth term.

Clashes have broken out near the security directorate office in the Smouha area of Alexandria every night between Nov.19-22. 2 protesters were killd over the course of the protests (1 coded in a previous event).

On 22 November 2011, villagers from Borei Keila community clashed with the police during a demonstration in Phnom Penh. Police officers beat at demonstrators, who in turn threw objects at the officers.

Nepali Congress cadres staged a demonstration in Kalikot headquarters Manma demonstrationing the recent seizure of land of their Kalikot district president's house by the Baidhya faction of Unified CPN-Maoist. NC cadres demonstrated saying the police had just been mute spectators when Maoist cadres started seizing land and threatened to chase the family out of their house.

Three American students were arrested by Egyptian police for throw petrol bombs at them. They are later released.
Rioters attack a Zambia Daily Mail vehicle leaving multiple injured

On 21 November 2011, demonstrations and clashes with security forces continue into the third day. 23 were reported killed while hundreds more have been injured (some estimates were as high as 1,750). Nearby buildings were set on fire. The military governing cabinet tenders their resignations in response to the violence, though most military officials refuse. 3 Americans students were arrested for allegedly throwing petrol bombs during the protests on Sunday.

They said that they should have to resign accepting their responsibility.
Students rally outside Syrias embassy in Algiers in support of uprising.

On 21 November 2011, demonstrators attempted to storm the Security Directorate building in Al Mansurah when police responded by firing rubber bullets and live ammunition, wounding a number of demonstrators. The demonstrations turned into hit-and-run attacks between the rioters and police. No fatalities were reported. [size=not reported]

On 21 November 2011, more than 2,000 demonstrators clashed with police in front of the Security Directorate in the town of Asyut with the former throwing bricks and stones and the latter responding with tear gas. A number of demonstrators were wounded although no number was recorded. [size=2,000]
Lady Reading Hospital (LRH) Peshawar employees continued their demonstration on the third day for the acceptance of their demands which included health professional allowance.

On Nov 21, Northern University Bangladesh (NUB) students ransacked parts of its building in the city's Tejgaon and blocked Kazi Nazrul Islam Avenue for around 15 minutes against NUB's decision to transfer them to a rented campus in Banani.
On Nov 21, Bangladesh Muktijoddha Sangsad formed a human chain in front of High Court in Dhaka protesting BNP Chairperson Khaleda Zia's reported bid to save the war criminals.

On Nov 21, people from seven unions in Chapainawabganj Sadar upazila formed a human chain in front of Chapainawabganj Press Club demanding steps to protect their areas from erosion by the Padma and Mohananda rivers.

notes: On 21 Nov, Jatiya Chhatra Dal of SUST unit staged a demonstration to protest the building plan of Tipaimukh dam at the ShahJalal University of Science and Technology (SUST), Sylhet sity.

Boycotting the NA, Shah had staged a sit-in at the entrance of the Parliament House in October after 14 people of the Hazara community - an ethnic minority that follows Shia Islam - were gunned down outside Quetta in the second such incident within a fortnight. Shah is still not attending the NA session and cintinues to protest to the governments indifference.

The Martyrs' Families and the People's Movement Injured Joint Struggle Committee staged a two-hour sit-in at the Prime Minister's residence in Baluwatar. The joint struggle committee is calling for application of the agreements the Government signed with the martyrs' families and the people injured during the 2006 People's Movement at different times. Participants staging the sit-in were infuriated and intensified their protest after learning that Prime Minister who was expected to meet them did not.
Hundreds of Liberian opposition supporters gathered in Monrovia Monday for a funeral march to honor the victims of a police shooting that marred disputed elections earlier this month.

On 21 November 2011, about 300 villagers from Kandal province delivered petitions to embassies in Phnom Penh. Afterwards, the villagers, involved in land disputes with private companies, marched to the provincial hall and called for Prime Minister Hun Sen to help them.
On November 21, in Sittwe (Sittwe, Rakhine), local activists were demonstrating for better supply of electricity in Rakhine. Police detained at least 10 of the activists.
The Jamaat-i-Islami (JI) held protests in multiple cities against the Federal Cabinet's decision to grant Most Favoured Nation (MFN) status to India.The JI demanded a ban on trade with India.

There were reports of clashes between protesters and security forces in near the security directorate office in the Smouha area of Alexandria. The clashes escalated from those reported on Monday, and left as many as 39 injured after rocks, rubber bullets and tear gas were traded between the two sides.

About 200 people from Don Mueang and Laksi districts of Bangkok and Mueang Ake housing estate of Pathum Thani gathered to demand the opening of Khlong Bang Khen sluice gate at Wat Thewa Sunthorn in Bang Khen district to drain floodwater from the areas. They demanded the government install at least 30 pumps to drain the water.
Some 300 Nonthaburi residents demonstrated outside city hall to demand immediate solutions to the flood waters there, which remain high after paralyzing their province for months.
Protesters marched in Taza against corruption and calling for a boycott of upcoming elections.

At least 1,000 protesters of the Feb 20 Movement gather and call for a boycott of parliamentary elections, believing the Kings recent reforms had not gone far enough. They carried a mock casket with "Parliamentary Elections" written across the side.
At least 2,000 protesters of the Feb 20 Movement marched to call for a boycott of parliamentary elections, believing the Kings recent reforms had not gone far enough.
At least 2,000 protesters of the Feb 20 Movement marched to call for a boycott of parliamentary elections, believing the Kings recent reforms had not gone far enough.

On 20 November 2011, thousands of rioters clashed with hundreds of soldiers and police in Tahrir Square; 11 are reported dead from clashing while over 700 were reported wounded. 40 police officers were wounded and 18 of the protesters were arrested. The police were trying to evict demonstrators who had camped out in the Square. Clashes between rioters and security forces were also reported at the Interior Ministry which is just a few blocks away from Tahrir Square. The Shura Council building was set on fire by a tear gas bomb.

On 20 November 2011, police at Cairo International Airport broke up a clash between supporters and opponents of the Bashar al Assad regime that took place as a plane form Syria landed at the airport. Neither injuries nor fatalities were reported. [size=50]
On 20 November 2011, Muslim Brotherhood students gathered and chanted slogans against the military outside Helwan University in Cairo. [size=not reported]

On 20 November 2011, clashes broke out between a group of lawyers and supporters of Al Nour Party candidates in front of the North Cairo courthouse in the Al Wayli neighborhood. No fatalities were reported.
Anti-military junta protests spread into other cites around Egypt. Police fired tear gas to disperse protesters in Suez.
Anti-military junta protests spread into other cites around Egypt. No report of police clashes.

On 20 November 2011, an Egyptian demonstrator was killed and 15 were wounded in protests against the country's military rulers in front of the security headquarters in the Smouha area of Alexandria. Clashes were reported between the protesters and security forces. Several thousand were reported to have taken part in the demonstrations.
On Nov 20, agitating students of Dhaka University (DU) took out a procession on the campus protesting the death of Nadia Sultana, a masters student of Department of Microbiology at DU.
On Nov 20, at least 20 activists of local BNP and its associate bodies were injured as police charged batons on their procession in Chandpur town.
On Nov 20, at least 10 people including a JSC examiner were injured during a clash between two groups of villagers over the boundary of their homes at Kadirpur village in Biswanath upazila.

Employees of Insurance Board (IB) launched a demonstration program in Kathmandu, which disrupted the day-to-day work at the head-office of the insurance sector regulator. At least one Ethiopian was killed and three other were injured as residents fought Ethiopian police forces in Bali-dhiig district of Togdheer Region in the breakaway region of Somaliland.

More than 200 residents of Lam Luk Ka gathered to demonstrate against FROC's order to close sluice gates at all three canals in tambon Bueng Thong Lang. There were also reports that locals near the sluice gates at Klong 10 destroyed the earth dike that had been built.

On 6 November 2011, dozens of Muslims who were praying during Eid al-Adha marched to Tahrir Square following their prayer and called for a halt to military courts, the release of political prisoners, and a swift transition to civilian rule in the country. [size=dozens]
On 6 November 2011, rioters set a fire on a railway near Sohag to denounce the nation-wide shortage of fuel.
Christian youths protest a recent attack during a worship service.
A Unity Party helicopter dropped thousands of election pamphlets across the city urging supporters to boycott runoff elections.
A small crowd gathered at the Congress for Democratic Change (CDC) for a "peace vigil" in support of Tubman, a candidate in the runoff elections.

assoc_actor_1: ANNISU(R): All Nepal National Free Students' Union (Revolutionary); Students (Nepal)
notes: The Ratna Rajya College Unit of the All Nepal National Free Students Union (ANNFSU) enforced an hour-long chakkajam in front of the college in Kathmandu, demanding that the government repeal its decision to hike public vehicle fares. No other details were reported.
Students and Civilians protest at the Natural Resources Development College
On Nov 5, Jatiyatabadi Mahila Dal formed a human chain before Jatiya Press Club in Dhaka demanding the release of Narsingdi district BNP President Khairul Kabir Khokon.

Some 100 Angolans took to the streets Saturday in central Luanda to demand recognition and compensation for a 1977 ruling party purge that killed several thousands in the wake of a failed coup.The march was organized by the May 27 Foundation, which wants the government to launch an inquiry into the events surrounding May 27, 1977, when two senior members of the ruling MPLA led a failed uprising against then-president Agostinho Neto.

Renewed protests against China by Tibetan exiles despite a protracted crackdown by security forces became violent with angry demonstrators throwing stones at baton-wielding cops as the latter tried to pull down portraits of the Dalai Lama and banners announcing a prayer ceremony for those who had laid down their lives for religious and political freedom in Tibet. Police in Nepal are hunting for a Tibetan woman who tried to pour kerosene oil on herself and set herself on fire but was prevented by remonstrating bystanders. The attempt made police sweep down on the Samdupling Tibetan settlement in Kathmandu valley and detain 18 people found carrying cans of kerosene.

The residents of Quetta staged protest on Friday against incident of firing between two rival groups due to which five persons sustained injuries. The enraged people staged protest, blocked Neechari road, Alamdaar road and adjacent areas by torching tyres.

On 4 November 2011, dozens of Freedom and Justice Party members marched in the Al Aguza district of Giza governorate as a way to show support for party members running in the upcoming elections. [size=dozens]

assoc_actor_1: YDA: Young Doctors Association; PMA: Pakistan Medical Association; Health Workers (Pakistan)
notes: Doctors of the public hospitals of provincial capital observed a complete strike at their respective hospitals against the registration of murder case against 5 doctors of Sheikh Zaid Hospital, office-bearers of Pakistan Medical Association said. A protest rally was brought out from Sheikh Zaid Hospital by PMA and YDA Shiekh Zaid in which the office-bearers of the associations said in the presence of the health care commission act police had registered an illegal FIR of 302 against their colleagues
The rain affected residents of different unioncouncils of Taluka Chambar staged a protest demonstration against the non provision of relief to them.
On Nov 4, twelve people, including two policemen, were hurt in a clash between police and garment workers in Gazipur, Chittagong.

Leaders of the Ahle Sunnat wal Jamaat (ASWJ), formerly known as the Sipah-e-Sahaba Pakistan (SSP) protested against the recent murders of seven activists. Maulana Aurangzeb Farooqui added that they would continue to protest the deaths of their activists until the government takes action.
In response to the cleric's murder, protestors took to the streets. They burnt tyres and chanted slogans against the government. Some protestors also resorted to aerial firing.
On 3 November 2011, dozens of Ghad Political Party supporters held a vigil in the Talaat Harb Square in solidarity with their detained leader, Ayman Nour. [size=dozens]

On 3 November 2011, a march commemorating the slain activist Mina Daniel arrived at the Ramses Square in the Shubra junction in the Al Sahil neighborhood of Cairo district. The marchers, which consisted of a large group of Coptic Egyptians, demanded the release of detainees from military prisons, the resignation of the Information Minister, and prosecution for those responsible for the deaths at Maspero. [size=not reported]

Lawyers community across the country including the Supreme Court Bar Association (SCBA) and Punjab Bar Association observed black day over imposition of emergency and suspension of constitution by former military ruler Pervez Musharraf. They took out rallies and boycotted court proceedings through out the country.

Lawyers observed Black Day to condemn state of emergency clamped by then army dictator General Pervez Musharraf and demanded his trial for abrogating the Constitution. They boycotted legal proceedings and hoisted black flags at Sindh High Court, Karachi & Malir District Bar Associations buildings.
Residents and police clash over shack destruction over two days in Gugulethu. Injuries not known.

On 3 November 2011, a group of Salafi Front supporters demonstrated in front of the Saudi Embassy in Duqqi area of Giza governorate, calling for the release of fellow members detained in Saudi Arabia. [size=not reported]

A group of teachers and students of the Faculty of law and political science and the Faculty of Economic Sciences and management of Tunis under the Tunis El Manar University, held a protest movement within the University grounds to claim respect for individual freedoms including the freedom of dress and the acceptance of the other.
On Nov 3, a hijacker was lynched and two others were injured by mob when they were trying to hijack an auto-rickshaw at Bhurbhuria on Narsingdi-Ameerganj road in Shibpur upazila.
On 03 November 2011, about 400 villagers from Meak Bei village in Prek Kak commune, in Kampong Cham, protested after workers from a private company attempted to clear their houses with excavators.
Sudanese police fired tear gas to disperse some hundreds of demonstrators who protested against the accidental killing of boy by the security forces several days ago.

On 2 November 2011, dozens of members of a group calling itself Movement for All Unemployed demonstrated in front of the Prime Minister's office in the Haidaq Al-Qubba neighborhood of Cairo. The group's members threatened collective suicide if the government did not provide them with public sector jobs. [size=dozens]

assoc_actor_1: UCPN(M): Unified Communist Party of Nepal (Maoist)
notes: Scores of Maoist hardliners, including members of parliament and former ministers, marched in an angry protest rally in Kathmandu, burning copies of a newly signed peace pact that promised to give fresh momentum to the wilting peace process, and threatening to pull out of the party. The demonstrators are asking their own comrade and prime minister to scrap the new peace agreement.

Hundreds of IDPs took to the streets of Wardhiigley district to demonstrate against food aid mismanagement and corruption. Hundreds of demonstrators complained about lack of food, water, sanitation and shelter and accused the TFG Food Aid Management Committee of diverting the food aid meant for the IDPs in Mogadishu.
Residents and police clash over shack destruction over two days in Gugulethu. Injuries not known.
A young man was killed during violent clashes on 2 November between some residents of the Sidi Saadi neighbourhood in Beni Messous on the heights of Algiers over rehousing policy.
Confrontations broke out between residents of the Sidi Saadi neighbourhood in Beni Messous on the heights of Algiers and those who had been rehoused, who used different knives and Molotov cocktails.

Pakistan Machine Tool Factory (PMTF) staged a protest in front of factory gate against the non-payment of their three-month salaries and ending some of their benefits. The workers closed the main gate of the factory whereas even the officials were unable to enter the factory. A dispute also broke out between the employees and CBA union representatives resulting in the injury of at least two persons including a union representative.
Women rally to protest role of Islamists
On Nov 2, angry local people torched a Kishoreganj bound train at Bashail in the district town Narsingdi in protest at killing of poura mayor Lokman Hossain. 10 people were injured during the event.

On Nov 2, Mayors, councillors and employees of Sirajganj municipalities formed human chain in front of Sirajganj municipality office to protest the killing of Narsingdi municipality Mayor Lokman Hossain.
On Nov 2, Hundreds of Chhatra League (BCL) activists agitated in Pabna town demanding removal of district unit BCL president and secretary.

On Nov 2, Hindus staged a demonstration in front of Nilphamari deputy commissioner's office protesting an alleged bid to grab the land of a temple by some unscrupulous people at Itakhola village in Nilphamari Sadar upazila.
On Nov 2, Mayors, councillors and employees of Manikganj formed human chain on the premises of Manikganj Press Club to protest the killing of Narsingdi municipality Mayor Lokman Hossain.

On Nov 2, at least 12 people were injured as the supporters of two local leaders of ruling AL and opposition BNP clashed in Kalai upazila of Joypurhat district. Clash erupted after a supporter of the BNP leader beat up local AL leader earlier.
Hundreds of students protested at has Tunis college to defend "academic and individual freedoms."

On 02 November 2011, about 15 villagers from among 386 families from Borei Keila community continued to protest outside Prampi Makara district hall, in Phnom Penh. The group urged the government to intervene in a contentious land dispute with Phanimex Company.

Senators from Federally Administrated Tribal Areas (FATA) protested against non-release of development funds for FATA and continuing drone attacks by coalition forces stationed in Afghanistan. Awami National Party (ANP) had also joined in protest demonstration to express solidarity.
Street vendors riot when police try to arrest them

On 01 November 2011, a group of 100 people protested outside Sihanoukville Municipal Hall. The group, who is facing eviction from their shelters near Sihanoukville Autonomous Port, demanded a resolution before they are forced to move.

Police detained more than 100 Tibetan exiles who were demonstrating against Chinese rule over their homeland. The Tibetan demonstrators who had gathered for a prayer meeting on the outskirts of Katmandu started chanting anti-China slogans, so the police detained the demonstrators in detention centers.

On 1 November 2011, a group of families of individuals killed on January 25th of that year carried out a protest vigil in front of the Welfare Building in the As-Sayyidah Zainab area of Cairo, calling for a speedy prosecution of those responsible for the killings. [size=not reported]

On 1 November 2011, a group of April 6th Movement supporters marched to Talaat Harb Square where they briefly scuffled with residents of the area before police broke up the fight. The group was marching against the continued detention of Alaa Abdel Fatteh, the death of other activists, and against the continued use of the emergency law. Neither injuries nor fatalities were reported. [size=unknown]

On 1 November 2011, lawyers protested outside the Egyptian Bar Association building in the Qasr Al-Nile neighborhood of Cairo against the President of the Association and called for a purge of the judiciary and for their involvement in monitoring the upcoming elections. [size=not reported]

On 1 November 2011, a group of roughly 25 journalists protested in front of the Egyptian parliament in the Haidaq al-Qubba neighborhood of Cairo against a Deputy Prime Minister for Political Development and Democratic Transformation, calling the individual corrupt.[size=25]

More than 3,000 Egyptians marched through downtown Cairo, protesting the militaries arrest of a prominent blogger-activist. The military says he is suspected of inciting Christian protesters to attack soldiers during an October 9th demo.

On Oct 31, 2011, Al-Azhar University students continued their sit-in for the eighth day in a row in Nasr City, Cairo, and detained the security personnel of the university building who managed to get out later. They were demanding the election of leaders, changing the student list, and amending law 103. [size=no report]

notes: On Oct 31, 2011, dozens of members of the Egyptian Federation of Independent Trade Unions and a number of candidates on the workers seat, organized a protest in front of 6th of October Elementary Court building in Giza Square, Giza, to denounce the refusal of the examination committee in the court to accept their candidacy papers on the seats of workers in the parliament. [size=dozens]
On Oct 31, 2011, dozens of South Sinai Bedouin tribesmen protested in Ras Sudr, South Sinai, demanding the release of Sinai detainees in Israeli prisons. [size=dozens]
PML-N held a rally in Peshawar against the attacks on PML-N offices in Sindh.
A group of 400 students of Tshwane University attack a group of security officers after a number of their colleagues were arrested for drunkenness.

PML-N workers staged a protest in front of the Karachi Press Club against the torching of their offices in different cities of Sindh in.They warned the government of holding more protests if their workers, who were arrested earlier in the day are not released.

On Oct 31, teachers and students of Pabna Shahid Fazlul Haque High School along with locals formed a human chain in the pabna town demanding exemplary punishment for the killers of Imran Hossain, a class nine student of the school.

On Oct 31, the investors under the banner of Bangladesh Capital Market Investors Oikya Parishad gathered in front of the DSE in Dhaka city and formed a human-chain after holding a press conference to protest the plunge in stock prices.

A group representing people with disabilities staged a protest in front of the Cabinet building, demanding equal rights.

[size=dozens]

On Oct 30, 2011, hundreds of students from Al Azhar University and some of the faculty demonstrated, blockading the university presidency building in Nasr City, Cairo, and preventing staff from entering and leaving. [size=hundreds]

On Oct 30, 2011, a number of air traffic controllers, organized a protest in front of the Civil Aviation Ministry's office in Al-Nozha, Cairo, to demand the cancellation of the decision to transfer them to the Air Academy. [size=several]

On Oct 30, 2011, dozens of workers from Misr Monofiya Spinning and Weaving Company held a protest in front of the headquarters of the Trade Union Federation in Al Azbakeyah, Cairo, to demand the head of the union's temporary committee to pay them urgent aid, especially with the approach of Eid Al-Adha. [size=dozens]

On Oct 30, 2011, hundreds of employees of the Grand Egyptian Museum organized a vigil in front of the headquarters of the museum in Al Haram, Giza, to demand employment of all temporary employees of the museum and the elimination of corruption and purge the museum from the remnants of the former regime. [size=hundreds]
Police arrest and detain a civil rights activist, sparking a protest.

On Oct 30, at least 15 people, including three cops and a poura councilor, were injured in a clash over a trifling matter at Hayat Kha village in Ulipur municipality, Kurigram.
On Oct 30, a human chain was formed by freedom fighters in Muktagachha demanding the early trial of war criminals.
On Oct 30, Garments workers blocked busy Rokeya Swarani in Dhaka's Shewrapara following death of a female RMG worker in an accident on the road.
On Oct 30, a human chain was formed by freedom fighters in Bogra demanding the early trial of war criminals.
Taxi drivers invaded the city police station, blocking traffic, to protest against the laxity of the law enforcement officers and the lack of security.

On Oct 29, 2011, dozens of citizens, political activists and political movements protested inside the High Court building in Cairo, to denounce the military trials of civilians, demanding that they be stopped and that all those referred to the military trials be referred to civilian ones. Residents of Laas Qoray held a demonstration protesting against commercial activities of Iranian fishing vessels in the area. Several thousand protesters in Cairo called on the ruling military on Friday to promptly transfer power to a civilian government and exclude old regime figures from politics. The group chanted "down with the military" and called on the ruling generals to "return to the barracks." The uprising was sparked in part by calls from activists on a Facebook page initially set up to protest that death of another young man, Khaled Said, after a beating by police.

Protesters clashed with soldiers and police in Cairo after a funeral procession for a man a rights group claims died from police torture after he was caught smuggling a mobile phone chip into his cell. Dozens of protesters hurled stones at soldiers and police after relatives of Essam Atta brought his coffined body to Tahrir Square. No report of injuries or causalities.

On Oct 28, 2011, a number of families and relatives of the prisoner Essam Ali Atta, who was killed after being transferred from his prison, staged a sit-in in front of Zeinhom morgue in Qasr Al-Nile, Cairo, while receiving the body of the victim, a number of political activists and youth of the April 6 Movement also took part in the demonstration. [size=several]

On Oct 28, 2011, hundreds of protesters including 6 April Youth staged a protest in front of the radio and television building in As Sabtiyyah, Cairo, to demand the cleansing of media from corrupt leaders, and the submission of information minister for trial on charges of sedition between Muslims and Copts, and a call for an end to torture in Egyptian prisons. [size=hundreds]

On Oct 28, dozens of citizens blocked the road in front of the entrance of Sheikh Zayed City in Giza, carrying a number of banners demanding retribution for the student who was killed after policemen shot him in the car in Sheikh Zayed City, they also set fire to the police car in front of Sheikh Zayed Hospital. [size=dozens]

On Oct 28, residents of Al-Manawat village, located in the center of Abu an Numrus city, Giza, blocked Egypt-Assiut highway, and closed the gas plant in Tamwah village, demonstrating against the non-fulfillment of their demands. [size=no report]
Kenyan youths gather to protest against the recent activities of al Shabaab.

Troops fired into the air in Sidi Bouzid on Friday morning to disperse a crowd trying to attack the offices of the regional government. Supporters of the Petition for Justice and Development Party, popular in Sidi Bouzid, were angered that it had been eliminated from the ballot over allegations of campaign finance violations.
PML-N staged a protest in Lahore against the PPP government.
A suspected thief is attacked and killed by a vigilante mob in the Nellmapius area.
Residents of Shaheed Benazirabad staged a protest demanded the removal of dangerous low lying electrical wires from residential areas.
Activists of different nationalist parties staged a protest in Dadu for the release of their arrested party leaders.
Rioters (DRC) from two opposing factions of UDPS clashed in Makiso, Kisangani. 4 injured, 1 seriously so.

On Oct 28, the National Committee to Protect Oil, Gas, Mineral Resources, Power and Ports started their four-day long march towards Sunetro in Sunamganj, from Dhaka's Jatiya Press Club in protest of the government's plan to employ foreigners in gas extraction from Sunetro Gas Field.

Several citizens of Zarzis held Friday afternoon, a peaceful demonstration in downtown to express their discontent for the lack of resources at the regional hospital of Zarzis and claim improvements and the human and material support in favor of this hospital.
Protest in Verulam when bail is granted to a charged killer.

On Oct 27, 2011, dozens of protesters gathered in Tahrir Square, Cairo, to denounce the military council's failure to respond to the demands of the people, and to hold presidential elections in order to hand over power to an elected president and government in mid-2012. [size=dozens]

On Oct 27, 2011, a number of employees of Al-Nasr Steam Boilers Company resumed their protest in front of the Council of Ministers in Cairo, to ask the director of the business sector to vote on the recommendations of the committee formed under his chairmanship to discuss the demands of workers. Dozens of Muslim inmates staged a demonstration which turned into a riot at the Pattani prison, alleging its staff had treated them unfairly. The riot, which was between groups of prisoners, left one inmate dead and two others injured. Investigators said the riot erupted when a group of 40 inmates assaulted other prisoners.

Police repulsed supporters of the former president Mubarak who attempted to storm the courthouse at Cairo's police academy where he was on trial. Some of the demonstrators were detained. The pro-Mubarak supporters also clashed with anti-Mubarak supporters inside and outside the courthouse. 11 people were injured in the clashes. 22 people were arrested, including a 1 member of April 6 Youth Movement. [size=no report]
Youths riot over the demolition of housing structures, throwing rocks and glass bottles, eventually getting into a long battle with police forces. Several injuries.

About 300 people rallied on September 3rd in Luanda's Independence Plaza, in one of the largest protests yet against President Jose Eduardo dos Santos's 32-year rule. Thousands of people took to the streets of Mogadishu for the second consecutive day to protest against the terms of the "Kampala Accords" and the resignation of the TFG Prime Minister. TFG security forces supported the demonstrations alongside of their duty to keep order. The demonstrations of 10/06 were far larger that what had occurred the day before and extended in most areas under TFG control. The crowd showed to be obviously hostile to the TFG President and Speaker of Parliament and went on attacking Medina and Muna hotels that are traditional hangouts of TFG MPs supporting these two leaders. Security guards in Medina Hotel fired at the crowd trying to approach the hotel, killing 1 person and injuring several others, triggering an angry reaction and the partial burning of the hotel. Several vehicles belonging to TFG MPs were set on fire. The Prime Minister called for people to stop the violence and get back home. Announcements were made that the demonstrations could extend in the following days.

On 04 January 2011, about 20 families living in Klaing Saing village in Russei Keo district gathered outside the Russei Keo commune hall, in Phnom Penh. They protested against the bulldozing of their land for the construction of a riverside park backed by petrol conglomerate Sokimex.
Police violently repress demonstrations
Huge protest at funeral for man who set himself on fire

assoc_actor_1: CHADEMA: Party for Democracy and Progress
notes: Following the violent dispersal of a protest earlier in the day, police engaged in running battles with rioting youths into the evening.

assoc_actor_1: CHADEMA: Party for Democracy and Progress
notes: A section of the busy Arusha-Moshi highway turned into a battlefield as heavily armed riot police moved in to break up a demonstration led by senior Chadema officials. Shortly after 1pm, police fired tear gas, prompting a near-stampede.
More than a hundred docker workers in the port of Algiers, observed a work stoppage on 4 January to protest against new measures relating to overtime compensation and shifts.
More than 300 Burmese migrant workers of the SYK Autopart Import-Export Co. Ltd protested against labour rights violations in Bangkok.

Twenty-two people were injured in a clash between agitated sugarcane farmers and police personnel along the Hariwan section of the East-West highway in Itahari. The clash occurred when the farmers were trying to block traffic. Of the injured, 15 are police personnel and the rest are farmers. The police fired more than two dozen tear gas shells during the clash.

Thousands of protesters, mainly Coptics, clashed with police as they protested against the Alexandria church bombing. 8 protesters were arrersted on charges of assaulting police officers and vandalism. 14 members of the security forces were injured by thrown rocks. They responded with tear gas and batons, injuring at least 10 protesters.

In Redayf in the southern mining region, a group of people, who were detained in connection with the 2008 social protests in the region and have been recently released, began an open sit-in. They were protesting for the release of people who were detained during the mining region unrest and the Sidi Bouzid protests.

Scores of students clashed with security forces in the Tunisian town of Tala and threw a burnt tire at a police centre while lawyers announced they will go on strike in protest over what they call police "abuses" against their colleagues.
More than 100 residents of Hangawatta and Banduragoda staged a protest against the school principal's decision to transfer a teacher of the area.
More than 100 residents of Hangawatta and Banduragoda staged a protest against the school principal's decision to transfer a teacher of the area.

The Centre for Human Rights Education held a protest outside the Lahore Press Club, demanding that the government pay more attention to the human rights situation in Pakistan. The protest was held on 3 January 2011.
Protests disrupted learning in several schools in with parents locking out head teachers whose pupils performed dismally in last years KCPE examination.

Protests disrupted learning in several schools in Kakamega County with parents locking out head teachers whose pupils performed dismally in last years KCPE examination. In Mumias district, parents stormed Etenje Primary School and forced out the head teacher.

Demonstrators blocked roads on 3 January in Tipaza, west of the capital, in protest against food prices and difficult living conditions.
Women activists from different NGOs protested against violence in Karachi and held the MQM responsible for the incidents during the protest. It took place in Peshawar on 3 January 2011.
On Jan 3, in Luxor, a hundred of students, professors and employees of the Faculty of Tourism held a protest in the afternoon, condemning Alexandria's attack. [size=hundred]
On Jan 3, in Al Azhar University, Cairo, Muslim Brotherhood members, students and faculty members held a protest to condemn Alexandria's attack on New Year's Eve. [size=no report]

On Jan 3, tens of students and professors from Ain Al Shams University, in Cairo, held a protest in front of Qasr Al-Zaafran campus at the university's campus, in solidarity with the victims of Alexandria's attack on New Year. [size=tens]

On 03 January 2011, about 200 residents from Boeung Kak area participated in a protest at Freedom Park, in Phnom Penh. They called for Inner Mongolia Erdos Hung Jun Investment Co, a Chinese firm which reportedly invested tens of millions of dollars in the area, to intervene in the dispute with the local company that is developing the lake.
On Jan 2, a "large number" of Christian Copts protested against Alexandria's bombing on New Year. They reportedly marched from Imbaba, Giza, to Maspero Television Building, Cairo. [size=no report]

On 02 January 2011, about 300 Yellow Shirt activists (PAD) protested in Sa Kaeo province, Thailand, across the border near Banteay Meanchey. The group protested against the arrest of seven Thais in Cambodia accused of entering a military base.

Agitating sugarcane farmers of Sarlahi district targeted a bus carrying Indian tourists to vent their anger over police intervention in their protest. The farmers had organized a three-hour blockade along the Sarlahi section of the East-West Highway to press the government to fix a minimum price for sugarcane. As the local administration deployed the police to clear the highway obstruction, a clash erupted between the law enforcement officers and the demonstrators. The demonstrators attacked a tourist bus at Hariaun and padlocked the Indushankar Sugar Mill in the district.

On Jan 2, in the evening, close to St George's Church, Bulaq neighbourhood, Cairo, hundreds of Christian Copts demonstrated in solidarity with the victims of Alexandria's bombing. Security Forces surrounded the rioters to prevent them from marching in the streets. Report mentions "small clashes" between rioters and Police Forces. [size=hundreds]
On Jan 2, Christian Copts staged a protest in front of Arcadia's Mall, in Bulaq, Cairo, to denounce the New Year's attack in Alexandria. [size=no report]
A vigilante mob kills a man after rumours he and recently "hanged a man."

Workers and youths in the Tunisian city of Sfax gathered in front of the local office of the Tunisian General Labour Union in solidarity with the population of Sidi Bouzid Province which was the site of two-week long social protests. The union members called for the freedom to demonstrate and freedom of expression and denounced the way security forces dealt with protestors in many Tunisian cities.
JSQM activists staged a protest in Qazi Ahmed outside the Press Club on 2 January 2011, to demand the release of a JSQM activist called Akash Mallah.

Coptic Christians held a demonstration at St. Marks Cathedral over the recent bombing of a Christian church in Alexandria. Protesters called for the sacking of the Minister of the Interior and arrest of those responsible. The protesters threw rocks and bottles, injuring "4 policemen and 38 security force officers". Egypts top Muslim cleric also had his car hit with stones as he went to see the Coptic Pope.
On January 2, in Jhenaidah city (Jhenaidah, Khulna), unidentified rioters killed three people during election-related rioting.
On January 2, in Gazipur city (Chandpur, Chittagong), teachers and employees of National University staged a protest against the termination of employees.
Around 2,000 Coptic Christians demonstrated in Al-Ezziyah against a bombing in Alexandria targeting Christians.

Coptic Christians, upset following a New Years Eve Mass bombing protest outside the targeted Church, denouncing public officials and puling one minister, a Muslim cleric with stones as he passed by. Police officers suffered light wounds when the rioters again threw stones at them. Many motorists cars were also hit with stones.

Coptic Christians protested against the Alexandria church bombing and denounced public officials. Police officers suffered light wounds when the rioters again threw stones at them. Many motorists cars were also hit with stones.

On Jan 2, following a protest on Jan 1, more than 1,000 Christian Copts staged another protest in the evening inside the Melawite diocese in Minya against Alexandria's bombing. The Archdiocese and Security Forces closed the doors of the diocese to prevent protesters from marching in the streets. [size=1,000]

On Jan 2, in Izbat Harfush village, Fayyum, in the evening, thousands of people participated in the funeral of a police agent killed by unidentified armed men who tried to steal his weapon. They reportedly staged a protest to demand justice. [size=thousands]

On Jan 2, after Sunday Mass, at St George Church in Mansoura, young people from various political movements set up a protest against terrorism, in solidarity with victims of Alexandria's attack on New Year's Eve. [size=no report]
On Jan 2, in the afternoon, tens of lawyers held a protest in front of the Lawyers Association's headquarters in Cairo to denounce New Year's bombing in Alexandria. [size=tens]

On Jan 2, government supporters in Alexandria set up a protest in front of the Alexandria ambulance station to denounce the recent bombing. Protesters chanted slogans denouncing terrorism and praising national unity. [size=no report]

On 1 January 2011, members of the People's Alliance for Democracy (PAD) rallied in front of Government House in khwaeng Dusit (Dusit, Bangok), calling on the government to pressure Cambodia to release the seven detained Thais immediately and to rapidly settle the border dispute with the neighbouring country.

Hundreds of protesters from various opposition groups including the MB demonstrated in the Shubra area of Cairo against a recent bombing at a Christian church and called for the resignation of the Interior Minister. Police were present to control the protest, but no incidents were reported.

BNP activists clashed with police on January 1 as law enforcers charged a roadside BNP rally in Rajshahi city. At least 50 people including BNP joint secretary Ruhul Kabir Rizvi and Rajshahi district BNP president Nadim Mostafa were injured in the clash.

At least 10 students were injured on January 1 as two rioting factions of Bangladesh Chhatra League (BCL) of Dhaka Homeopathic College unit clashed during New Year's celebration feast on their premises in Dhaka city.

Following a car bomb attack against a church, Coptic Christians, some of whom were armed with knives, rioted and clashed with police who used tear gas to disperse them. During the riots a number of police cars were burned. At least one person was injured by pellet shot.
JSQM Hyderabad Chapter staged a protest outside Hyderabad Press Club on 1 January 2011 to demand the arrest of the accused killers of Majid Memon, a party activist.
On Jan 1, 1 person was killed and 15 were injured in a clash between two groups of villagers at Noagaon village (Katiadi, Kishoreganj) over a land dispute.
More than 60 people were injured in two separate clashes between supporters of Awami League (AL) and 4-party alliance (BNP) candidates at Sathia and Sujanagar in Pabna city on 1 January.

notes: On January 1, in Manikganj city (Manikganj, Dhaka), JCD activists and police clashed during a demonstration rally. 20 people including 8 police were injured.
Students of Sabaragamuwa University in Belihuloya village, Sabaragamuwa, staged a protest on 1 January demanding the reopening of the University following a ragging incident.

The protest took place on 1 January 2011, which Aman Ittehad declared as Solidarity Day.

notes: Six Maoists close to the UCPN (Maoist) vice-chairman in Baitadi district were beaten up and injured by supporters of the party chairman. No other details were reported other than the victims were being treated at hospitals.

On Jan 1, inside the Melawite diocese in Minya, more than 150 Coptic Christians organized a protest in solidarity with the victims of New Year's bombing in Alexandria, denouncing the lack of security. Security Forces interfered to prevent them from marching in the streets. [size=150]
On January 1st, Aman Ittehad staged a protest demonstration in AJK as part of a nation-wide agitation against violence.

An angry crowd in Magude district, in Maputo province, attacked three police officers, included the Magude district commander. The attackers were demanding an explanation for the fatal shooting by a policeman of a three year old child.
